&lt;h3&gt;Use Cases for Azure Functions and Logic Apps&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Because Functions are code-based, you can write, execute, and test them on your local workstation. Any debugging can take place without involving your production cloud environment or provisioning additional (potentially costly) test resources in the cloud. This is also more efficient for your developers.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As mentioned above, Functions also offer more flexibility due to their basis in powerful programming languages. They are also portable into and out of Azure. Some common scenarios for using Functions include:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Timer-based triggers&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Azure service event processing&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;SaaS event prcessing&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Serverless web app and mobile app architecture&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Real-time stream processing or bot messaging&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Logic Apps are preferable when you don�t wish to leverage developer resources and instead use the GUI. They are better suited to integrations as many connectors are available out of the box. Therefore Logic Apps can reduce your time to market in an automation scenario. Some common uses for Logic Apps include:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;SaaS event processing&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Timer-based or content-based triggers and routing&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Data ingestion or transformation&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Business Processes&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Integration between Azure cloud services&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;

